<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN and VICTOR VALLE, Arts and entertainment reports from The 
Times, national international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal appeals panel has cleared the way for hotel managers to rent movies 
to guests to watch in their rooms, without having to worry about legal action. 
The U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed a lower court decision in a 
copyright infringement case filed by Columbia Pictures Industries, Paramount 
Pictures, Walt Disney Productions and four other studios. The movie makers 
filed suit against La Mancha Private Club and Villas in Palm Springs, claiming 
it was staging public performances of copyrighted material by allowing guests 
to rent movies in a hotel gift shop to show in their rooms. Public showings of 
films without licensing agreements violate federal copyright laws. The appeals 
court affirmed an earlier ruling, saying that "while the hotel may be 'open to 
the public,' a guest's hotel room, once rented, is not." ALEENE MacMINN and 
VICTOR VALLE 
</P>
</TEXT>
