<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEBRASKA RECRUIT VICTOR STACHMUS DIES OF LEUKEMIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Victor Stachmus, 19, a Nebraska football scholarship winner last year, died 
early today at the UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles, where he was being 
treated for leukemia, a Nebraska football coach said. 
</P>
<P>
Stachmus, who was from McAlester, Okla., had been hospitalized for two weeks in 
the UCLA center for chemotherapy treatments. He had been transferred there from 
the M. D. Anderson Medical facility in Houston, where he had been receiving 
treatments since September. 
</P>
<P>
"Victor has shown a great amount of courage and was at peace with himself when 
he died," Nebraska coach Tom Osborne said. "It was a very tragic situation, but 
his spirit was high. It is unfortunate that he never did get to play at 
Nebraska, because it was something he really wanted to do." 
</P>
<P>
Stachmus died at 1:30 a.m. PST, according to Nebraska assistant football coach 
Ron Brown. 
</P>
<P>
sh First Oklahoman to Sign 
</P>
<P>
Stachmus, who graduated from McAlester High School last spring, was the first 
Oklahoma high school recruit to sign a national letter of intent with Nebraska. 
He was admitted to St. Francis Hospital in Tulsa, Okla., last April, when it 
was discovered he had leukemia. 
</P>
<P>
After a month of hospitalization last spring, doctors said Stachmus' disease 
was in remission, and he planned to enroll at Nebraska this semester. 
</P>
<P>
A week ago, Stachmus received more than 1,600 cards and letters from Nebraska 
football fans who participated in a "Go Big Vic," campaign to let him know that 
Cornhusker fans still thought of him. 
</P>
<P>
"The Stachmus family and the coaching staff at the University of Nebraska would 
like to thank all the people for their cards and prayers during Victor's 
hospital stay," Osborne said. 
</P>
<P>
"His mother said Victor told her before he passed away that he was spiritually 
ready to die and that was a great comfort for the family," said Brown. 
</P>
<P>
"He was a very wonderful young man," said Allen Wadsworth, Stachmus' high 
school football coach and McAlester's athletic director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
